      Don=E2=80=99t put it in email
   =20
 =20

One fact of antitrust law is that if you are an executive at=C2=A0a big com=
pany, or at a medium-sized company contemplating a merger, you will think t=
hings like =E2=80=9Cwe need to grow our market share=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cw=
e need to grind our competitors into dust,=E2=80=9D but if you say stuff li=
ke that =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly, if you say it in writing, in emails or=
 memos or presentations=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0antitrust regulators might find=
 it and sue to break up your company or stop the merger or whatever, and th=
ey will use your words to prove that you are doing anti-competitive things =
to become a monopoly. This is not intuitively obvious=C2=A0to you at all: Y=
ou are just a normal competitive businessperson looking to do more business=
; surely trying to gain market share is good=C2=A0for competition, not bad.=
 But there are forms of words, ways of expressing things, that=C2=A0look ba=
d to antitrust regulators, and there are others that don=E2=80=99t, and mos=
t normal people don=E2=80=99t know which are which.
  [11]

Antitrust lawyers do, though, so it is common in mergers for the antitrust =
lawyers to sit down with their clients and say =E2=80=9Chere are the words =
not to use, and here are the words to use instead.=E2=80=9D And if you work=
 at a company that gets big enough organically, and that starts looking a l=
ittle monopolish, at some point it will hire some antitrust lawyers who wil=
l also have that talk with everyone.=C2=A0
But there is a problem, which is that the talk=C2=A0also=C2=A0uses the bad =
words. The talk itself looks suspicious! If you are going around telling pe=
ople not to use the bad words, that suggests a guilty conscience; you tell =
people not to say =E2=80=9Ccrush the competition=E2=80=9D because you know =
that your plans to crush the competition are monopolistic. Or that=E2=80=99=
s what antitrust regulators will argue. Also  the talk is probably in writi=
ng:

Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Google is on trial in Washington DC over US allegat=
ions that it illegally maintained a monopoly in the online search business.=
 Executives of the Mountain View, California-based behemoth have known for =
years that the company=E2=80=99s practices are under a microscope, and have=
 encouraged its employees to avoid creating lasting records of potential pr=
oblematic conduct, government lawyers allege. =E2=80=A6
As far back as 2003, Google managers circulated unambiguous instructions on=
 phrases to avoid to ensure they don=E2=80=99t come across like monopolists=
.
We =E2=80=9Chave to be sensitive about antitrust considerations,=E2=80=9D G=
oogle Chief Economist Hal Varian wrote in a July 2003 memo, unearthed by go=
vernment lawyers who are suing Alphabet. =E2=80=9CWe should be careful abou=
t what we say in both public and private.=E2=80=9D
One phrase to avoid, Varian said: =E2=80=9CCutting off their air supply.=E2=
=80=9D He was referring to a quip used years earlier by then-Microsoft Corp=
 Chief Executive Officer Steve Ballmer, when his company was under federal =
antitrust scrutiny.
Another no-no, according to a 2009 Varian missive: =E2=80=9CMarket share.=
=E2=80=9D Instead, when referring to Google=E2=80=99s portion of the search=
 market, use the term =E2=80=9Cquery share.=E2=80=9D Penny Chu, the recipie=
nt of Varian=E2=80=99s email, responded in the affirmative. =E2=80=9CYes, a=
bsolutely.=E2=80=9D Such instructions constitute =E2=80=9Cthe one big thing=
 I remember from all that Legal training,=E2=80=9D Chu wrote, ending the se=
ntence with a sideways smiley. =E2=80=A6
During the trial, [Justice Department lawyer Kenneth] Dintzer pressed Varia=
n on the question of =E2=80=9Cantitrust training=E2=80=9D at Google. When V=
arian said he couldn=E2=80=99t remember whether he=E2=80=99d taken it, Dint=
zer tried to jog his memory. =E2=80=9CAvoid references to markets or market=
 shares or dominance,=E2=80=9D Dintzer said, citing an internal document.

It really is a hard problem to solve. One option is you hire the antitrust =
lawyers and they walk door to door, visiting every person=E2=80=99s office =
and having an in-person chat impressing on everyone the importance of using=
 the good words and not the bad words. Maybe the antitrust lawyers, like, d=
ress up in hooded robes and play terrifying sound effects and generally try=
 to put on a memorable theatrical presentation (with nothing in writing!) t=
o scare everyone into remembering not to use the bad words. People are gonn=
a forget, and then you have to remind them,=C2=A0not in writing, never in w=
riting. You show up at their office in the robe again, with a scythe, and y=
ou point a bony finger at them and=C2=A0in a booming desolate voice you sho=
ut =E2=80=9CIT=E2=80=99S QUERY SHARE.=E2=80=9D Still, even if you never put=
 it in writing, the regulators could ask about it at trial.
Really this stuff should be taught in college, so that every company can wa=
sh its hands of it. The last semester at Wharton everyone should have to ta=
ke a class called Don=E2=80=99t Put It In Email that is just, like, =E2=80=
=9Cwe know that when you go out into the world you will occasionally engage=
 in legally ambiguous actions, here are some best practices for not getting=
 in trouble over them, some forms of words and communications methods not t=
o use and some others to use instead.=E2=80=9D Then the college=C2=A0is res=
ponsible for the =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t put it in email=E2=80=9D instructio=
n,=C2=A0but not for the legally ambiguous actions (Wharton=C2=A0is not star=
ving Google=E2=80=99s competitors of oxygen), while the companies are respo=
nsible for the legally ambiguous actions but not for any=C2=A0trainings tha=
t look like evidence of a guilty conscience.

