10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Basis trade</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A simple model of US Treasury bonds<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0could go something like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The US government borrows a lot of mo=
ney and has a very long time horizon, so it wants to borrow a lot of money =
for terms of 10 or 20 or 30 years.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Lots of asset owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0pension funds, university endowments, =
people saving for retirement =E2=80=94=C2=A0also have a long time horizon a=
nd want to earn a safe return, so they want to lend the government money fo=
r terms of 10 or 20 or 30 years.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a nice and simple story. Pensions have=
 long-dated liabilities (future pension payments), so they buy long-dated a=
ssets (long-term Treasuries) to match them, which means that they can buy T=
reasury bonds for long periods and hold them until they mature.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not a perfect story. If you run a pensio=
n fund, you probably do not just buy long-term Treasuries to cover your fut=
ure liabilities. Treasuries are very safe assets, which means they don=E2=
=80=99t pay that much, and you want to get paid more. You probably invest i=
n other stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccredit,=E2=80=9D corporate bonds and =
private credit and asset-backed securities =E2=80=94=C2=A0to earn a bit mor=
e yield.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much of this credit stuff, though, has shorter=
 terms than 30 years; there is not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>much 30-year cor=
porate borrowing. If you buy a lot of seven-year corporate bonds, and you h=
ave very long-dated liabilities, there will be a mismatch. You are taking a=
 lot of interest-rate risk: Sure those bonds pay a lot of interest now, but=
 they mature in seven years, and if interest rates are lower in seven years=
 you will earn less interest. If your liabilities are long term, you want t=
o earn a lot of interest over the whole term. You want the duration of your=
 assets to match the duration of your liabilities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you buy more duration with Treasury=C2=A0<e=
m>futures.=C2=A0</em>Treasury futures are synthetic contracts that give you=
 the interest-rate exposure of Treasury bonds=C2=A0but without putting up m=
uch cash upfront. You put up about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY21lZ3JvdXAuY29tL21hcmtldH=
MvaW50ZXJlc3QtcmF0ZXMvdXMtdHJlYXN1cnkvMzAteWVhci11cy10cmVhc3VyeS1ib25kLm1hc=
mdpbnMuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB225587b1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> $3,900</a> and ge=
t economic exposure to $100,000 of Treasury bonds: If long-term Treasury pr=
ices go up by 1%, you make $1,000 on your initial $3,900. If interest rates=
 go down, the price of Treasury bonds will go up, and you will make money, =
which will compensate you for your reduced future interest earnings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a more nuanced story of what pension f=
unds and other long-term asset managers do.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> But our original simple story described a whole trade: Pensions bought=
 Treasuries, and the government sold them, and the trade made sense for bot=
h of them. Now we have a trade that makes sense for pension funds, but who =
is on the other side? The government is not selling them Treasury futures.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, you need some intermediary to provide=
 the service of=C2=A0<em>transforming=C2=A0</em>Treasuries (sold by the gov=
ernment) into=C2=A0Treasury futures (bought by pension funds). This service=
 is called the =E2=80=9Cbasis trade,=E2=80=9D and the intermediaries are us=
ually hedge funds and proprietary trading firms.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> Here is a=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy9oZWRnZ=
S1mdW5kcy1iaWctYmV0LWFnYWluc3QtdHJlYXN1cnlzLWlzbnQtd2hhdC15b3UtdGhpbmstZmFi=
YTM4YzU_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf83e57cd" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Wall Street Journal article</a>=C2=A0about the basis trade, which has cause=
d problems in recent years and is now making a comeback:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A popular way for hedge funds to profit from b=
ond trading while minimizing their exposure to swings in the market, the ba=
sis trade exploits the price difference between Treasurys and Treasury futu=
res. The resurgence is attracting fresh scrutiny from Wall Street because p=
revious meltdowns have rattled global markets. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge funds buy Treasurys, then bet against Tr=
easury futures by selling contracts promising delivery of a bond on a speci=
fic date at a preset price. Instead of betting on the direction of bond mar=
kets, the trade seeks to take advantage of small differences in the securit=
ies=E2=80=99 prices.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trade works because large asset managers l=
ike pension funds often prefer buying Treasury futures that require less up=
-front cash than actual bonds. That tends to make the contracts slightly mo=
re expensive than the bonds, creating a window for speculators to take adva=
ntage.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> Futures prices typically converge toward bond prices as their settleme=
nt date approaches.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The differences are small, so hedge funds juic=
e returns by borrowing from big banks in the overnight funding markets=E2=
=80=94often putting little, if any, cash up front. Leverage can reach extre=
me levels: Hedge funds had more than $550 billion of Treasury trades at the=
 end of last year backed by just $10 billion of their own money, Fed resear=
ch found.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvious objection is that if you have $550=
 billion of Treasuries backed by $10 billion of your own money, and the val=
ue of Treasuries drops by 2%, then all of your money is gone, you have to d=
ump Treasuries, everyone else is dumping them at the same time and there is=
 a crisis.=C2=A0This is an exaggeration, because if the value of Treasuries=
 drops by 2% then probably you made 2% on your futures and you=E2=80=99re m=
ore or less fine, but still there is not a ton of margin for error, and mis=
takes have been made:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basis trade had been subdued since a dash =
for cash in March 2020 forced hedge funds to rapidly unwind their positions=
, straining the market for Treasurys =E2=80=94 meant to be the world=E2=80=
=99s easiest investment to buy and sell. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the 2020 Covid market crash, hedge fund=
s=E2=80=99 unwinding of leveraged strategies including the basis trade spil=
led across markets, helping send the Dow Jones Industrial Average to its wo=
rst losses since 1987 and forcing the Fed to step in.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now it is back:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Fed=E2=80=99s fight against inflation and =
the U.S. government=E2=80=99s wave of borrowing reignited the trade, analys=
ts say. Higher yields and worries about a recession have asset managers sco=
oping up long-term bond futures. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Given those uncertainties and with a potential=
 recession up in the air, =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s natural to see record hedgi=
ng in the Treasury market,=E2=80=9D said Agha Mirza, global head of rates a=
nd OTC products at CME Group.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a pension fund, the 10-year Treasur=
y is at a high-relative-to-recent-history 4.25%, and you worry it will go b=
ack down if there is a recession, then you will want to lock in a lot of th=
at rate=C2=A0while earning more today on corporate credit. So you will load=
 up on Treasury futures. And someone will sell them to you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you are a pension fund. The people selling=
 you these futures are not.=C2=A0<em>You=C2=A0</em>have a long time horizon=
.=C2=A0<em>They=C2=A0</em>are doing this as a trade.=C2=A0<em>They=C2=A0</e=
m>are in the business of buying a ton of Treasuries and selling a ton of Tr=
easury futures when there is demand for the futures, and not doing that whe=
n there isn=E2=80=99t. They don=E2=80=99t have a giant pot of long-term loc=
ked-up pension money to buy Treasuries with. They have a little bit of thei=
r own cash ($10 billion), and a lot of borrowed money ($540 billion), to bu=
y the Treasuries that they transform into futures.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So there is another intermediary here: When pe=
nsions are buying Treasury futures, they are buying them from hedge funds a=
nd prop trading firms that own the underlying raw materials (Treasuries) us=
ed to manufacture the futures. But those hedge funds need another raw mater=
ial: the cash they use to buy the Treasuries.=C2=A0<em>That=C2=A0</em>money=
 is mostly borrowed, in the repo market, where the hedge funds put up their=
 Treasuries as collateral for short-term cash loans from banks and money-ma=
rket funds and other investors looking to park cash somewhere safe for the =
short term.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, our simple model at the beginning was t=
hat=C2=A0long-time-horizon pension funds buy and hold long-term bonds from =
the long-time-horizon government. The more accurate model is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The long-time-horizon government sell=
s long-term bonds.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Those bonds are=
 bought by short-time-horizon hedge funds using borrowed money.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The money is borrowed from short-time-horizon=
 repo lenders.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The hedge funds use=
 the bonds to manufacture=C2=A0Treasury futures, which they sell to long-ti=
me-horizon pension funds.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It all kinda works! The beginning makes sense,=
 and the end makes sense, and the middle is=C2=A0<em>efficient</em>. It let=
s the pension funds be nimbler with their cash and lend to real businesses =
and get higher yields. But that efficiency comes with risk. The long-time-h=
orizon government and the long-time-horizon pensions don=E2=80=99t really h=
ave to care about market movements; if they dealt with each other directly,=
 they could just do the trade once and wait for it to mature 30 years later=
. Once you introduce highly leveraged short-term intermediaries, market mov=
ements can blow up the trade and lead to margin calls and forced selling.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjkvdWstcGVuc2lvbnMtZ290LW1hcmdpbi1jYWxscz9jbXBpZD1C=
QkQwOTE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHR=
lciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBdca1a5e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> talked last year</a> about =E2=80=9Cliability-dri=
ven investment=E2=80=9D at UK pension funds, which led to a brief meltdown =
in the gilt (UK government bond) market. The story there is different, but =
it has similar features: Pension funds, rather than matching their liabilit=
ies with long-dated gilts, bought things with higher returns and hedged the=
ir interest-rate risk with derivatives. This meant that if interest rates m=
oved, the pensions got margin calls and could get blown up. I wrote:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This all makes total sense, in its way. But no=
tice that you now=C2=A0<em>have borrowed short-term money to buy volatile f=
inancial assets</em>. The thing that was so good about pension funds =E2=80=
=94 their structural long-termism, the fact that you can=E2=80=99t have a r=
un on a pension fund: You=E2=80=99ve ruined that! Now, if interest rates go=
 up (gilts go down), your bank will call you up and say =E2=80=9Cyou used o=
ur money to buy assets, and the assets went down, so you need to give us so=
me money back.=E2=80=9D And then you have to sell a bunch of your assets =
=E2=80=94 the gilts and stocks that you own =E2=80=94 to pay off those marg=
in calls. Through the magic of derivatives you have transformed your safe b=
oring long-term pension fund into a risky leveraged vehicle that could get =
blown up by market moves.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I know this is bad but I find something aesthe=
tically beautiful about it. If you have a pot of money that is immune to ba=
nk runs, over time, modern finance will find a way to make it vulnerable to=
 bank runs. That is an emergent property of modern finance. No one sits dow=
n and says =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s make pension funds vulnerable to bank run=
s!=E2=80=9D Finance, as an abstract entity, just sort of does that on its o=
wn.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Finance really does do that!=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is not just finance being a clever li=
ttle scamp; there is something essential about it. Last week, Lev Menand an=
d Josh Younger published a fantastic paper titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly9qb3Vybm=
Fscy5saWJyYXJ5LmNvbHVtYmlhLmVkdS9pbmRleC5waHAvQ0JMUi9hcnRpY2xlL3ZpZXcvMTE5M=
DAvNjAxOA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75d20778" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Money and the Public D=
ebt: Treasury Market Liquidity as a Legal Phenomenon</a>.=E2=80=9D Alexandr=
a Scaggs wrote about it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNDMzM2FhMmItNzc3Y=
S00YzllLThiZmMtYTI0MmIzZDIxYzVm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBadb69744" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 at FT Alphaville</a>, and Adam Tooze discussed it in <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly9hZGFtdG9vemU=
uc3Vic3RhY2suY29tL3AvY2hhcnRib29rLTIzOC1tYWtpbmctYW5kLXJlbWFraW5n/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB45f00c6b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> his newsletter</a>, and I cannot really =
do justice to everything that is in it, but it is a good thing to read if y=
ou are thinking about the basis trade.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is basically a history of the US Treasury m=
arket from the perspective of=C2=A0<em>how Treasuries are turned into money=
.=C2=A0</em>The very simple story of Treasuries is =E2=80=9Cthe government =
wants to borrow long-term, some people want to lend long-term, and they get=
 matched up.=E2=80=9D But that story has never been completely true: Treasu=
ries are not just a long-term investment for pension funds and retirement s=
avers; they are also the preeminent=C2=A0<em>safe asset</em>, which means t=
hat a lot of people who own Treasuries will have occasion to sell them to r=
aise cash. There needs to be a buyer: When everyone wants to sell Treasurie=
s for cash, there needs to be someone who can quickly come up with a lot of=
 cash to buy all the Treasuries. Menand and Younger write:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The high degree of convertibility =
between Treasury securities and cash =E2=80=94 the market=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Cliquidity=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 depends upon entities that can create new, =
money-like claims to buy Treasuries. Sometimes the government=E2=80=99s cen=
tral bank has issued these claims directly, as in March 2020; other times t=
hese claims were issued by central bank-backed instrumentalities, such as b=
anks and select broker-dealers.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Who can =E2=80=9Ccreate new, money-like claims=
=E2=80=9D to quickly buy any Treasury supply? The most obvious answer is =
=E2=80=9Cthe central bank=E2=80=9D: The Federal Reserve (1) creates dollars=
 and (2) buys Treasuries, so it is a natural supplier of Treasury liquidity=
. But that is sort of a=C2=A0disfavored answer: Everyone understands that i=
t is bad for a government to finance itself by=C2=A0<em>printing money=C2=
=A0</em>(it=E2=80=99s inflationary), so a system in which the Treasury sold=
 all of its bonds directly to the Fed for newly created dollars would be ba=
d.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Menand and Younger argue =E2=80=9Cthat Ame=
rican public finance has long been closely intertwined with the American mo=
netary framework,=E2=80=9D and they trace the history of (1) who could issu=
e =E2=80=9Cmoney-like claims=E2=80=9D to buy Treasuries and (2) how the gov=
ernment and the Fed supported those buyers and markets. The history has fou=
r parts:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The national banking system, in which=
 Congress chartered national banks to print money and use the money to buy =
Treasuries; here, =E2=80=9Cfiscal-monetary entanglement was relatively tran=
sparent.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The Federal Rese=
rve system, in which the Fed printed the actual dollars, while=C2=A0<em>ban=
ks=C2=A0</em>issued deposits (money-like claims) and, for some time,=C2=A0u=
sed a lot of the money to buy Treasuries.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">The primary dealer system, in which banks stopped buying so many Tr=
easuries, but primary dealers (investment banks) bought Treasuries and fund=
ed them in the repo market. Repo, Menand and Younger=C2=A0argue, is a money=
-like claim, a short-term safe place for cash investors to park their money=
,=C2=A0and it was created and supported by the Fed=C2=A0to allow primary de=
alers to efficiently provide liquidity for Treasuries.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">The current system: After 2008, the primary dealer sys=
tem atrophied (many big dealers=C2=A0became banks), and now Treasury liquid=
ity comes from a combination of (1)=C2=A0<em>actual banks</em>, which can <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3Rhcn=
R1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVR=
kYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwOTE0=
JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1807a66b" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>  fund Treasuries by issuing deposits</a>, and (2) hedge funds, prop tradi=
ng firms and other not-quite-primary-dealers that use the repo market to fi=
nance their Treasury trades.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In all of the later configurations, the Fed si=
ts somewhere behind the market: When things go wrong, the Fed supports whoe=
ver (banks, primary dealers, now hedge funds) provides Treasury liquidity. =
They write:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Subsequent changes=C2=A0to market =
structure pushed substantial Treasury dealing further beyond the bank regul=
atory perimeter, leaving public finance increasingly dependent on high-freq=
uency traders and hedge funds =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cshadow dealers.=E2=80=9D T=
he near-money issued by these intermediaries proved highly unstable in 2020=
. Policy makers are=C2=A0now focused on reforming Treasury market structure=
 so that Treasuries remain the world=E2=80=99s most liquid asset class. Suc=
cessful reform likely requires a legal framework that, among other things, =
supports elastic intermediation capacity through balance sheets that can ex=
pand and contract as needed to meet market needs.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Treasuries can never be a=C2=A0<em>pure=C2=A0<=
/em>long-term buy-and-hold investment for everyone; somebody needs to be re=
ady to buy and sell them. That somebody will need short-term funding, and t=
hat short-term funding will create risks, and the Fed will have to stand be=
hind=C2=A0the market to sort out those risks.</p>
