<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Arm IPO</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The standard mechanism of the initial public o=
ffering is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company hires some banks to sell so=
me shares to the public for the first time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">The banks and company get together and come up with some estimate=
 of value and then go out and market the shares at some price range based a=
round that estimate.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They go out t=
o investors, pitch the company, and get orders at different prices.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The goal is to be =E2=80=9Coversubscribed=
,=E2=80=9D to have orders for many more shares than they are selling, so th=
at there is demand for the shares once they start trading. The bankers want=
 some investors=C2=A0<em>not </em>to get the shares that they asked for, so=
 that they have to go out and buy them in the market the next day, so that =
the investors who=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>get shares have someone to sell to=
. They want a healthy market, with supply and demand.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">The banks work for the company (they get paid a fee by =
the company), but they have mixed loyalties. The investors who buy the shar=
es are also customers of the banks, often big customers who pay the banks a=
 lot of fees and do a lot of trades with the banks. The banks want their co=
rporate client to be happy, but they also want their investor clients to be=
 happy.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This tension is=C2=A0<em>t=
he point=C2=A0</em>of the IPO: Companies hire banks to do IPOs because the =
banks have relationships with investors, because the banks are in a web of =
favors and obligations with the investors that they can use to sell the sha=
res. If the banks were not somewhat looking out for the investor clients, t=
hey would not be able to effectively sell the corporate client=E2=80=99s sh=
ares. =E2=80=9CNo conflict, no interest.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">Anyway, at the end of the process the banks come to the com=
pany and say, like, =E2=80=9Cwe have gotten a lot of good orders, and we ar=
e three times oversubscribed at $53 per share, and five times oversubscribe=
d at $52, and 10 times oversubscribed at $51, and 15 times oversubscribed a=
t $50, so let=E2=80=99s price at $51.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">And then the client says =E2=80=9Cwait you said we have orders=
 to buy three times the shares we are selling at $53 per share, and you wan=
t us to sell the shares at $51? Isn=E2=80=99t that leaving a lot of money o=
n the table?=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And then the=
 bankers say =E2=80=9Cyou don=E2=80=99t understand how this works, it is in=
 your long-term interests and also our long-term interests for the stock to=
=C2=A0<em>trade well</em>, for it to go up after this offering is complete,=
 and so we want to make sure there=E2=80=99s enough demand. It would be a d=
isaster if the stock dropped on the first day. You will be a long-term repe=
at user of the capital markets, you will come back to investors for money, =
you will pay your employees in stock, you want the stock to be attractive a=
nd trade up; you don=E2=80=99t want to take every last penny today at the e=
xpense of long-term investor relationships.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">This advice is basically not wrong, though it probably i=
mplies that investors have longer memories than they actually do.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company is like =E2=80=9Cfine $51.=E2=
=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The stock doubles the next =
day.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sorry, actually, this was the standard mechani=
sm of IPOs a few years ago, when big =E2=80=9CIPO pops=E2=80=9D (where the =
stock doubles the day after the company goes public) were common, which led=
 to companies trying things like <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMTEvZGlyZWN0LWxpc3RpbmdzLWFyZS1hLXRoaW5nLW5vdz9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQwOTE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB731c0a96" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  direct listings</a> to leave less money on =
the table. The standard mechanism of IPOs now is like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company calls some banks about sell=
ing some shares to the public for the first time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">The banks are like =E2=80=9Cehhh kind of a rough IPO market=
 right now, better wait.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a middle ground; some companies are s=
till going public these days. But the IPO market is still a bit shaky, and =
everyone is more sensitive about not knocking it over. <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTQvY2hpcC1kZXNpZ25lci1hcm0tcy1pc=
G8td2FzLXByaWNlZC1mb3Itc21vb3RoLXRyYWRpbmctZGVidXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxNDIzX01P=
TkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm0=
9MjMwOTE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa3a06cd2=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">  For instance</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SoftBank Group Corp. satisfied its ambitions f=
or Arm Holdings Plc by raising $4.87 billion in the year=E2=80=99s biggest =
initial public offering, while resisting the temptation to try for more.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A smooth trading debut from the chip designer =
on Thursday could help revive a weak IPO market and provide a boost for upc=
oming listings from companies like Instacart Inc. and Birkenstock Holding L=
td. At the IPO price, Arm is valued at about $54.5 billion, according to Bl=
oomberg News calculations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arm=E2=80=99s offering was oversubscribed more=
 than 10 times, people with knowledge of the matter have said, which means =
investor interest exceeded supply at the price range of $47 to $51 a share =
and could help buoy the stock once trading begins.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In setting the price for the IPO, Masayoshi So=
n, SoftBank=E2=80=99s founder, chairman and chief executive officer, signal=
ed that he was unwilling to push things too far even if it meant leaving a =
bit of money on the table.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the final price-setting meeting Wednesday, =
some bankers and executives made the case for a higher price, with some of =
the debate centering on whether $52 made sense, people familiar with the ma=
tter said, asking not to be identified because the meeting was private. Son=
 joined the discussion and chose $51, saying it wasn=E2=80=99t worth riskin=
g a healthy debut for $100 million or so in additional proceeds, they said.=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=C2=A0<em>bankers=C2=A0</em>told him to go =
with $52 and he said =E2=80=9Cnah let=E2=80=99s do=C2=A0$51,=E2=80=9D the e=
xact opposite of every 2019 IPO. Arm opened for trading today at 12:19 p.m.=
 with <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288=
423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTQvc29=
mdGJhbmstcy1hcm0taW5kaWNhdGVkLXRvLW9wZW4taGlnaGVyLWluLW5ldy15b3JrLWRlYnV0P2=
NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZ=
XdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDkxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB3c51d56a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  a price of $56.10</a>, then rose a bit =
in early trading. A=C2=A0<em>nice=C2=A0</em>IPO pop: Up a bit, but not so m=
uch that you=E2=80=99re embarrassed about the money you left on the table.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be fair, it is Masayoshi Son, who is a part=
icularly long-term repeat user of the capital markets. The Financial Times =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYTRkYzg1NGItY2RmOS00YzEzLWI5NzMtZjM5YjNmY=
TkxN2E0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6ae204c2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> noted last week</a>:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As well as retaining more than 90 per cent of =
a company that Son believes will underpin the future of computing, SoftBank=
 will also be able to lean on the newly listed company as a big source of f=
inancing. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSoftBank has been wanting to monetise=
 Arm for years,=E2=80=9D said Kirk Boodry, an analyst at Astris Advisory. =
=E2=80=9CArm is a quality asset, with punchy revenues and good margins. The=
y can hold on to and still have the cash to use in other areas =E2=80=94 in=
 that respect it=E2=80=99s a perfect replacement for Alibaba.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you sell $5 billion of a $54 billion compan=
y and keep the other $49 billion so you can borrow against it later to rais=
e cash, you care a lot more about the long-term value of the company than y=
ou do about maximizing today=E2=80=99s sale price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Byrne Hobart also <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZGlmZi5jby=
9hcmNoaXZlL25vcnRoLWtvcmVhcy1lY29ub215LW1haW50YWluaW5nLWEtcG9zaXRpdmUtdHJhZ=
GUtYmFsYW5jZS1ieS1leHBvcnRpbmctYmFkcy1hbmQtZGlzc2VydmljZXMv/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB09aedefd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> points out</a> that =E2=80=9CArm has a long =
list of strategic investors in the chip industry who have committed to taki=
ng a stake in the company,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Ca large chunk of [the=
 shares sold in the IPO] will be locked up by these buyers.=E2=80=9D This i=
s probably good for the stock price (a lot of the big investors in the IPO =
<em>won=E2=80=99t</em>=C2=A0be selling the first day), which means that Son=
 could probably get away with being more aggressive in pricing. On the othe=
r hand, it means that if he=E2=80=99s more aggressive in pricing he=E2=80=
=99s getting more money for SoftBank at the expense of Arm=E2=80=99s strate=
gic customers. Ordinarily in an IPO, the banks have relationships with the =
investors and want to make the investors happy, but the issuer is less inte=
rested in that goal. Here Arm probably has stronger relationships with the =
investors than the banks do.</p>
