adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Executive pay accounting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are the board of directors of a small a=
mbitious company that intends to disrupt and remake the whatever industry, =
but has not done so yet, probably the way you should pay your chief executi=
ve officer is (1) give her enough cash to pay her rent and (2) promise to m=
ake her very rich if the company actually works out. The exact mechanics of=
 that promise are flexible, but one pretty standard approach is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Give her a reasonable cash salary; an=
d</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Award her a huge slug of stock o=
ptions, at the <em>beginning</em> of the journey to disrupting and remaking=
 the industry, that will be worth, like, $5 billion if the company ends up =
being worth $50 billion. But if the company ends up being worth $0, they=E2=
=80=99ll be worth zero. And if the company just sort of muddles along doing=
 okay but never really disrupts or remakes anything, they will=C2=A0<em>als=
o=C2=A0</em>be worth zero: They will only pay off if the company gets reall=
y big. They are a stretch goal, a huge reward for huge success; they are no=
t meant to reward the CEO comfortably for modest success, but to encourage =
her to take big swings.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not the only way to do it, and boards =
that try to do it this way do not always follow through rigorously. (If the=
 company does okay-but-not-great, but the CEO is doing her best and the boa=
rd likes her, they might modify her options or give her more so that she st=
ill gets rich without real success.) But the appeal of this approach is obv=
ious, grounded in theory, aligned with shareholders and not uncommon. In th=
e state of the world where the CEO gets rich, the shareholder have also got=
ten rich, which is what the shareholders want.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the <em>accounting </em>is weird. As a mat=
ter of accounting, what happens is that you give the CEO a one-time grant o=
f options whose payout is something like =E2=80=9C$5 billion if the company=
 gets to $50 billion and $0 if it stays under $5 billion,=E2=80=9D or whate=
ver, and then an accountant throws that into a Black-Scholes calculator and=
 computes that the options have a fair market value,=C2=A0<em>now</em>, of =
$100 million or whatever, and then you disclose that value as the CEO=E2=80=
=99s =E2=80=9Ccompensation=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Cthis year=E2=80=9D in your=
 securities filings.=C2=A0And then journalists cheerfully report that your =
CEO gets =E2=80=9Cpaid=E2=80=9D $100 million =E2=80=9Cper year,=E2=80=9D an=
d that she is one of the highest-paid CEOs in the country despite your comp=
any being kind of small and not having had much success.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And you say, well, of course we are small and =
haven=E2=80=99t had much success; the point of the options grant is to chan=
ge that. The options will cost you $5 billion if the company works out grea=
t and $0 if it doesn=E2=80=99t. They didn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=
=9D cost you $100 million now, and the CEO certainly didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<e=
m>get=C2=A0</em>$100 million now: The calculated fair market value of the o=
ptions today might be $100 million, but she can=E2=80=99t sell them, and sh=
e will never get <em>any</em> value for them unless the company succeeds. T=
he $100 million value is, crudely, the $5 billion value of the options in t=
he success case times the 2% chance of achieving it.<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cworth=E2=80=9D $100 million in expectation,=
 but 98% of the time it will end up worth zero.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMDUvbG90cy1vZi1iYW5rcy1tZWFucy1sb3RzLW9mLWJhbmstbWVy=
Z2Vycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6539d5c6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked in July</a> about an artic=
le titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9tZWV0LXRoZS1jZW9zLX=
doby1wdWxsLWluLW1vcmUtdGhhbi0xMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1hLXllYXItODQwOWFmZTA_bW9kPWhwX=
2xpc3RiX3BvczU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17f764c8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Meet the CEOs Who=
 Pull In More Than $100 Million a Year</a>,=E2=80=9D and I made some of the=
se points, particularly about the CEO of=C2=A0=E2=80=9CCS Disco, a cloud-se=
rvices provider that caters to attorneys and [had] a market capitalization =
of about $500 million.=E2=80=9D Giving the CEO of a $500 million company=C2=
=A0$100 million in annual pay seems odd,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but of course CS Disco didn=E2=80=99t do that. They gave him a bi=
g one-time grant of options with a $109 million fair market value, but the =
options (1) have a strike price of $32 and (2) vest at prices starting at $=
150 and going up.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The $32 strike price was the company=E2=80=99s initial public off=
ering price, but by the time we talked about it the stock was at $8.40 and,=
 I wrote, =E2=80=9Cthe=C2=A0<em>most likely=C2=A0</em>value of this $109 mi=
llion pay package is zero dollars.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.288423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
idXNpbmVzcy9jZW8td2l0aC0xMTAtbWlsbGlvbi1wYXktcGFja2FnZS1pcy1zdWRkZW5seS1vdX=
QtNzkwN2M1NmY_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe06c64bc" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">an update today</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A big payday doesn=E2=80=99t always keep a chi=
ef executive employed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just over a year after CS Disco=C2=A0sharehold=
ers approved a CEO pay package worth nearly $110 million =E2=80=94 one of t=
he biggest of 2022 =E2=80=94 the company=E2=80=99s co-founder and chief exe=
cutive, Kiwi Camara, resigned with little explanation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His departure, disclosed in a securities filin=
g on Monday, could mean Camara loses the stock options that made up nearly =
all of the pay package. Camara couldn=E2=80=99t be immediately reached for =
comment.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">CS Disco shares fell nearly 20% Tuesday follow=
ing the disclosure. Shares in the company, which provides software used by =
lawyers, are trading below $8 after going public at $32 in July 2021. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under the terms of his employment agreement an=
d equity awards, Camara would forfeit the 4.37 million options he received =
in May last year if he departed before the company met certain stock-price =
targets, ranging from $150 to $900 a share. CS Disco hasn=E2=80=99t traded =
above about $66 a share, a level it last reached in 2021.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, right, he had a deal that would pay him a=
 lot of money if he could get the stock up above $150, and when it became c=
lear that that was not going to happen, he left, leaving behind a pay packa=
ge that was manifestly worth zero dollars.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense that is the disadvantage of payi=
ng your CEO like this: If she takes a big swing and misses and the stock=C2=
=A0<em>falls=C2=A0</em>rather than rising, she will give up, because there =
is no hope of achieving the milestones that you set for her. But in another=
, more accurate, sense that=E2=80=99s why you set the milestones! You wante=
d the company to take a big swing and disrupt its industry, and if it doesn=
=E2=80=99t work out you don=E2=80=99t want the CEO sitting around comfortab=
ly collecting a big check.</p>
