<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One fact of antitrust law is that if you are a=
n executive at=C2=A0a big company, or at a medium-sized company contemplati=
ng a merger, you will think things like =E2=80=9Cwe need to grow our market=
 share=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe need to grind our competitors into dust,=E2=
=80=9D but if you <em>say</em> stuff like that =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly,=
 if you say it in writing, in emails or memos or presentations=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0antitrust regulators might find it and sue to break up your compan=
y or stop the merger or whatever, and they will use your words to prove tha=
t you are doing anti-competitive things to become a monopoly. This is not i=
ntuitively obvious=C2=A0to you at all: You are just a normal competitive bu=
sinessperson looking to do more business; surely trying to gain market shar=
e is <em>good=C2=A0</em>for competition, not bad. But there are forms of wo=
rds, ways of expressing things, that=C2=A0look bad to antitrust regulators,=
 and there are others that don=E2=80=99t, and most normal people don=E2=80=
=99t know which are which.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Antitrust lawyers do, though, so it is common =
in mergers for the antitrust lawyers to sit down with their clients and say=
 =E2=80=9Chere are the words not to use, and here are the words to use inst=
ead.=E2=80=9D And if you work at a company that gets big enough organically=
, and that starts looking a little monopolish, at some point it will hire s=
ome antitrust lawyers who will also have that talk with everyone.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a problem, which is that the talk=
=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>uses the bad words. The talk itself looks suspicio=
us! If you are going around telling people not to use the bad words, that s=
uggests a guilty conscience; you tell people not to say =E2=80=9Ccrush the =
competition=E2=80=9D because you know that your plans to crush the competit=
ion are monopolistic. Or that=E2=80=99s what antitrust regulators will argu=
e. Also <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32711630.2=
88423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjMtMDktM=
TQvZ29vZ2xlcnMtdG9sZC10by1hdm9pZC13b3Jkcy1saWtlLXNoYXJlLWFuZC1idW5kbGUtdXMt=
c2F5cy1sbWoyN2JobD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWl=
sJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA5MTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbm=
V5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB58cd193b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the talk is probably =
in writing</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Google is on trial in =
Washington DC over US allegations that it illegally maintained a monopoly i=
n the online search business. Executives of the Mountain View, California-b=
ased behemoth have known for years that the company=E2=80=99s practices are=
 under a microscope, and have encouraged its employees to avoid creating la=
sting records of potential problematic conduct, government lawyers allege. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As far back as 2003, Google managers circulate=
d unambiguous instructions on phrases to avoid to ensure they don=E2=80=99t=
 come across like monopolists.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We =E2=80=9Chave to be sensitive about antitru=
st considerations,=E2=80=9D Google Chief Economist Hal Varian wrote in a Ju=
ly 2003 memo, unearthed by government lawyers who are suing Alphabet. =E2=
=80=9CWe should be careful about what we say in both public and private.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One phrase to avoid, Varian said: =E2=80=9CCut=
ting off their air supply.=E2=80=9D He was referring to a quip used years e=
arlier by then-Microsoft Corp Chief Executive Officer Steve Ballmer, when h=
is company was under federal antitrust scrutiny.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another no-no, according to a 2009 Varian miss=
ive: =E2=80=9CMarket share.=E2=80=9D Instead, when referring to Google=E2=
=80=99s portion of the search market, use the term =E2=80=9Cquery share.=E2=
=80=9D Penny Chu, the recipient of Varian=E2=80=99s email, responded in the=
 affirmative. =E2=80=9CYes, absolutely.=E2=80=9D Such instructions constitu=
te =E2=80=9Cthe one big thing I remember from all that Legal training,=E2=
=80=9D Chu wrote, ending the sentence with a sideways smiley. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the trial, [Justice Department lawyer K=
enneth] Dintzer pressed Varian on the question of =E2=80=9Cantitrust traini=
ng=E2=80=9D at Google. When Varian said he couldn=E2=80=99t remember whethe=
r he=E2=80=99d taken it, Dintzer tried to jog his memory. =E2=80=9CAvoid re=
ferences to markets or market shares or dominance,=E2=80=9D Dintzer said, c=
iting an internal document.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It really is a hard problem to solve. One opti=
on is you hire the antitrust lawyers and they walk door to door, visiting e=
very person=E2=80=99s office and having an in-person chat impressing on eve=
ryone the importance of using the good words and not the bad words. Maybe t=
he antitrust lawyers, like, dress up in hooded robes and play terrifying so=
und effects and generally try to put on a memorable theatrical presentation=
 (with nothing in writing!) to scare everyone into remembering not to use t=
he bad words. People are gonna forget, and then you have to remind them,=C2=
=A0<em>not in writing</em>, never in writing. You show up at their office i=
n the robe again, with a scythe, and you point a bony finger at them and=C2=
=A0in a booming desolate voice you shout =E2=80=9CIT=E2=80=99S QUERY SHARE.=
=E2=80=9D Still, even if you never put it in writing, the regulators could =
ask about it at trial.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Really this stuff should be taught in college,=
 so that every company can wash its hands of it. The last semester at Whart=
on everyone should have to take a class called Don=E2=80=99t Put It In Emai=
l that is just, like, =E2=80=9Cwe know that when you go out into the world =
you will occasionally engage in legally ambiguous actions, here are some be=
st practices for not getting in trouble over them, some forms of words and =
communications methods not to use and some others to use instead.=E2=80=9D =
Then the college<em>=C2=A0</em>is responsible for the =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99=
t put it in email=E2=80=9D instruction,=C2=A0but not for the legally ambigu=
ous actions (<em>Wharton=C2=A0</em>is not starving Google=E2=80=99s competi=
tors of oxygen), while the companies are responsible for the legally ambigu=
ous actions but not for any=C2=A0trainings that look like evidence of a gui=
lty conscience.</p>
